00:02:21.270 --> 00:02:26.570
So the first part I'd
like to speak about is--

00:02:26.570 --> 00:02:29.530
this is actually a tale
of my time at Microsoft.

00:02:29.530 --> 00:02:31.800
And bizarrely enough,
we have someone here

00:02:31.800 --> 00:02:35.150
who was actually there at the
time on the very same team.

00:02:35.150 --> 00:02:38.730
So he can verify that I'm
not embellishing this.

00:02:38.730 --> 00:02:42.480
And this section is
called "Chat Wars."

00:02:42.480 --> 00:02:46.980
And it begins with a
quote from Grace Hopper,

00:02:46.980 --> 00:02:50.490
"It's easier to ask forgiveness
than it is to get permission."

00:02:50.490 --> 00:02:52.620
And now you'll see why.

00:02:52.620 --> 00:02:53.730
[LAUGHS]

00:02:53.730 --> 00:02:56.250
At 22, when I was just
out of college and still

00:02:56.250 --> 00:02:58.020
a green software
engineer, I thought

00:02:58.020 --> 00:03:00.420
America Online and AOL won.

00:03:00.420 --> 00:03:02.940
The battle made the front
page of the "New York Times."

00:03:02.940 --> 00:03:05.059
The public was beginning
to care about code.

00:03:05.059 --> 00:03:06.600
This wasn't the code
that would crack

00:03:06.600 --> 00:03:09.060
the secrets of mathematics or
the nature of the universe,

00:03:09.060 --> 00:03:12.030
but it was the lifeblood
of our economy and society.

00:03:12.030 --> 00:03:14.160
It was the summer
of 1999, and people

00:03:14.160 --> 00:03:16.410
were starting to realize
that the internet and the web

00:03:16.410 --> 00:03:18.570
were becoming a new
dynamic circulatory

00:03:18.570 --> 00:03:22.650
system for informations,
coordination, and life itself.

00:03:22.650 --> 00:03:24.660
The summer before my
final year of college,

00:03:24.660 --> 00:03:26.490
I interned as a
software engineer

00:03:26.490 --> 00:03:27.900
at Microsoft in Redmond.

00:03:27.900 --> 00:03:29.490
I was assigned to
the group that was

00:03:29.490 --> 00:03:32.760
building MSN Messenger Service,
Microsoft's instant messaging

00:03:32.760 --> 00:03:33.420
app.

00:03:33.420 --> 00:03:36.900
And after receiving my degree, I
went on to join them full time.

00:03:36.900 --> 00:03:39.780
The unwieldy name was cooked
up by Microsoft's marketing

00:03:39.780 --> 00:03:42.030
department which had a
reputation for always picking

00:03:42.030 --> 00:03:44.130
the clunkiest and least
imaginative product

00:03:44.130 --> 00:03:47.640
names: Buddy List, C
U C Me, MSN Messenger.

00:03:47.640 --> 00:03:49.920
No, it was MSN
Messenger Service,

00:03:49.920 --> 00:03:52.410
but I'll call it
"Messenger" for short.

00:03:52.410 --> 00:03:54.930
At the time, the big
players in instant messaging

00:03:54.930 --> 00:03:59.280
were AOL Instant
Messenger, Yahoo, and ICQ.

00:03:59.280 --> 00:04:01.710
AOL Instant Messenger--
AIM for short--

00:04:01.710 --> 00:04:03.420
had tens of millions of users.

00:04:03.420 --> 00:04:05.430
AOL had become the
country's biggest dial-up

00:04:05.430 --> 00:04:07.920
provider in the mid '90s
by blitzing mailboxes

00:04:07.920 --> 00:04:09.090
with CD-ROMs.

00:04:09.090 --> 00:04:12.450
And all AOL users
automatically became AIM users.

00:04:12.450 --> 00:04:15.000
Yahoo and ICQ each
had millions of users.

00:04:15.000 --> 00:04:17.838
These are paltry numbers
by the standards of 2018,

00:04:17.838 --> 00:04:19.379
but they were
meaningful in the '90s.

00:04:21.930 --> 00:04:27.070
After my team finished
developing the client code,

00:04:27.070 --> 00:04:30.040
we had some downtime while
waiting for the server team

00:04:30.040 --> 00:04:31.776
to finish their
Hotmail integration.

00:04:31.776 --> 00:04:33.400
We couldn't release
without their work.

00:04:33.400 --> 00:04:35.440
We fixed every
bug we could find.

00:04:35.440 --> 00:04:37.480
One of the problems
was getting new users

00:04:37.480 --> 00:04:39.520
to join Messenger when
so many people already

00:04:39.520 --> 00:04:41.810
used other chat programs.

00:04:41.810 --> 00:04:46.030
Unlike email, which
has the standard SMTP

00:04:46.030 --> 00:04:48.997
format across all programs,
these chat networks

00:04:48.997 --> 00:04:50.080
didn't talk to each other.

00:04:50.080 --> 00:04:52.950
AOL didn't talk to Yahoo
which didn't talk to ICQ,

00:04:52.950 --> 00:04:54.730
and none of them
would talk to us.

00:04:54.730 --> 00:04:56.380
AOL had the largest user base.

00:04:56.380 --> 00:04:59.050
So we discussed the
possibility of adding code

00:04:59.050 --> 00:05:02.290
to allow Messenger to log into
two servers simultaneously,

00:05:02.290 --> 00:05:05.200
Microsoft's and AOL's, so that
users could see their Messenger

00:05:05.200 --> 00:05:07.090
and AIM buddies on a
single list and talk

00:05:07.090 --> 00:05:09.010
to AIM buddies via Messenger.

00:05:09.010 --> 00:05:11.326
We called it "interop."

00:05:11.326 --> 00:05:13.970
AIM's protocol was
known as OSCAR,

00:05:13.970 --> 00:05:17.170
stood for acronym for Open
System for Communication

00:05:17.170 --> 00:05:18.666
in Realtime.

00:05:18.666 --> 00:05:20.760
It was undocumented.

00:05:20.760 --> 00:05:24.730
So me and my mentor at the
time signed up for AIM accounts

00:05:24.730 --> 00:05:27.610
and watched the AIM client talk
to the server using a network

00:05:27.610 --> 00:05:28.540
monitor.

00:05:28.540 --> 00:05:30.430
I saw the protocol
that AIM was using.

00:05:30.430 --> 00:05:33.040
My mentor Chris had
figured out a large chunk

00:05:33.040 --> 00:05:33.921
of OSCAR this way.

00:05:33.921 --> 00:05:35.920
And after he left the
team, I picked up his work

00:05:35.920 --> 00:05:36.794
and finished the job.

00:05:40.500 --> 00:05:43.210
So, you know, did
AOL notice that there

00:05:43.210 --> 00:05:45.520
were some odd messages heading
their way from Redmond?

00:05:45.520 --> 00:05:46.480
Probably not.

00:05:46.480 --> 00:05:47.980
They had tens of
millions of users.

00:05:47.980 --> 00:05:51.380
And we were mimicking their
protocol reasonably well.

00:05:51.380 --> 00:05:53.966
But I thought this little stunt
would be deemed too dubious

00:05:53.966 --> 00:05:55.840
and excised from Messenger
before it shipped.

00:05:55.840 --> 00:05:57.400
But management liked it.

00:05:57.400 --> 00:06:01.690
So on July 22, 1999, Microsoft
entered the chat markets

00:06:01.690 --> 00:06:05.980
with MSN Messenger Service
complete with a AOL interop.

00:06:05.980 --> 00:06:08.380
No one had warned
AOL of our gambit.

00:06:08.380 --> 00:06:09.910
And they weren't
happy with what we

00:06:09.910 --> 00:06:14.350
termed our "unauthorized
interoperability."

00:06:14.350 --> 00:06:16.450
Quickly, they blocked
Messenger from connecting

00:06:16.450 --> 00:06:19.060
to their servers by veering
their protocol messages in ways

00:06:19.060 --> 00:06:20.650
we hadn't anticipated.

00:06:20.650 --> 00:06:23.440
Users who tried to contact
their AIM buddies from Messenger

00:06:23.440 --> 00:06:25.690
would receive a pop-up
instant message saying,

00:06:25.690 --> 00:06:29.540
"Use an authorized AOL client
at this link," with the URL.

00:06:29.540 --> 00:06:32.440
But as long as Messenger sent
exactly the same protocol

00:06:32.440 --> 00:06:34.810
messages to the AOL
servers, AOL wouldn't

00:06:34.810 --> 00:06:37.210
be able to detect that
a user was on Messenger.

00:06:37.210 --> 00:06:39.070
So I took the AIM
client and meticulously

00:06:39.070 --> 00:06:40.990
checked for differences
in what it was sending

00:06:40.990 --> 00:06:43.510
and then changed our client
to mimic it once again.

00:06:43.510 --> 00:06:45.970
Messenger users received an
upgrade with this new fix.

00:06:45.970 --> 00:06:50.890
And because this was the dial-up
days, the client was tiny.

00:06:50.890 --> 00:06:53.880
It was literally 300 K. It
was not even a megabyte.

00:06:53.880 --> 00:06:57.174
But AOL, again, caught on and
switched their protocol up.

00:06:57.174 --> 00:06:59.590
We matched their client again,
pushed out another upgrade.

00:06:59.590 --> 00:07:02.230
We went back and forth
at least a dozen times.

00:07:02.230 --> 00:07:05.080
At one point, AOL
sneakily excluded users

00:07:05.080 --> 00:07:08.174
logging on from Microsoft
headquarters IPs

00:07:08.174 --> 00:07:10.090
from their changes so
that we would be unaware

00:07:10.090 --> 00:07:12.970
that either Messenger users
were receiving an error message.

00:07:12.970 --> 00:07:15.520
After an hour or two of
scratching our heads,

00:07:15.520 --> 00:07:18.040
a team member sick at home
notified us that, yes,

00:07:18.040 --> 00:07:19.880
she was getting disconnected.

00:07:19.880 --> 00:07:22.180
And a shout-out
to Kara for doing

00:07:22.180 --> 00:07:26.950
that amazing work [LAUGHS]
when we were all going crazy.

00:07:26.950 --> 00:07:30.060
Microsoft and AOL were
both tech titans in 1999.

00:07:30.060 --> 00:07:32.260
Soon, the press got
a hold of the story.

00:07:32.260 --> 00:07:35.410
On July 24, the "New York
Times" printed "In Cyberspace,

00:07:35.410 --> 00:07:37.400
Rivals Skirmish Over "Messaging.

00:07:37.400 --> 00:07:40.900
"AOL kept blocking us," wrote
the paper of record, quote,

00:07:40.900 --> 00:07:42.610
"but Microsoft
refused to roll over.

00:07:42.610 --> 00:07:44.200
Late Friday, the
software giant said

00:07:44.200 --> 00:07:46.950
that it revised its MSN
Messenger program to circumvent

00:07:46.950 --> 00:07:48.910
America Online's roadblock.

00:07:48.910 --> 00:07:51.490
Within hours, America Online
answered that challenge

00:07:51.490 --> 00:07:52.240
with a new block."

00:07:52.240 --> 00:07:52.825
[LAUGHTER]

00:07:52.825 --> 00:07:54.366
It was like reading
about a wrestling

00:07:54.366 --> 00:07:57.850
match in which I was the
mysterious masked challenger.

00:07:57.850 --> 00:07:59.590
OK, so another quote.

00:07:59.590 --> 00:08:06.580
This is from the great
20th century polymath Jacob

00:08:06.580 --> 00:08:07.940
Aronofsky.

00:08:07.940 --> 00:08:10.750
"Progress is the exploration
of our own error."

00:08:10.750 --> 00:08:13.330
And I think anyone who's
been a software engineer sure

00:08:13.330 --> 00:08:14.990
knows that.

00:08:14.990 --> 00:08:17.054
So the messenger war was a rush.

00:08:17.054 --> 00:08:19.720
Climbing into work every morning
to see whether the client still

00:08:19.720 --> 00:08:24.150
worked with AOL was thrilling,
even if it usually wasn't.

00:08:24.150 --> 00:08:26.320
When it wasn't working, I
looked through the reams

00:08:26.320 --> 00:08:27.640
of protocol messages
to figure out

00:08:27.640 --> 00:08:30.056
what had changed, fixed the
client, tried to get an update

00:08:30.056 --> 00:08:31.850
out the same day.

00:08:31.850 --> 00:08:34.510
I had no idea who my adversaries
were, but I'd been challenged,

00:08:34.510 --> 00:08:35.909
and I wanted to win.

00:08:35.909 --> 00:08:38.110
And our users cared, too,
and they wanted us to win.

00:08:38.110 --> 00:08:40.780
And this was, you know, having
actual users on your side

00:08:40.780 --> 00:08:44.169
at Microsoft and those days
was actually somewhat unusual.

00:08:44.169 --> 00:08:46.660
[LAUGHING] So AOL tried
different tactics.

00:08:46.660 --> 00:08:49.847
At one point, I thought
that they were identifying

00:08:49.847 --> 00:08:51.430
the Microsoft client
because it wasn't

00:08:51.430 --> 00:08:54.460
downloading the advertising
that the AOL client downloaded.

00:08:54.460 --> 00:08:56.860
So I updated our client
to download it all

00:08:56.860 --> 00:08:58.730
and throw it away.

00:08:58.730 --> 00:09:00.469
AOL included mysterious
protocol messages

00:09:00.469 --> 00:09:02.760
that didn't seem to affect
their client but broke ours.

00:09:02.760 --> 00:09:04.000
So I fixed that.

00:09:04.000 --> 00:09:06.340
One day, I came in
to see this embedded

00:09:06.340 --> 00:09:09.740
in the messages from
the AOL server, "Hi.

00:09:09.740 --> 00:09:10.600
-Mark."

00:09:10.600 --> 00:09:12.520
It was a little
missive from engineer

00:09:12.520 --> 00:09:15.420
to engineer, hidden from the
corporate media and PR worlds

00:09:15.420 --> 00:09:16.960
that were arguing over us.

00:09:16.960 --> 00:09:18.910
I felt solidarity with
him even though we

00:09:18.910 --> 00:09:21.500
were on opposing sides.

00:09:21.500 --> 00:09:24.070
In the press, AOL was
pushing propaganda

00:09:24.070 --> 00:09:26.440
about how Microsoft was
behaving like an evil hacker

00:09:26.440 --> 00:09:28.120
by asking for AOL passwords.

00:09:30.724 --> 00:09:31.930
But this wasn't true.

00:09:31.930 --> 00:09:33.970
But we were allowed
only to respond

00:09:33.970 --> 00:09:35.080
through the PR department.

00:09:35.080 --> 00:09:37.850
My team was sealed off,
but our code wasn't.

00:09:37.850 --> 00:09:40.870
And then, one day, AOL
stopped blocking us.

00:09:40.870 --> 00:09:42.730
It was strange to
encounter sudden silence

00:09:42.730 --> 00:09:45.222
as though the enemy had abruptly
yielded the battlefield.

00:09:45.222 --> 00:09:46.930
And while I wanted to
believe we had won,

00:09:46.930 --> 00:09:50.285
I suspected AOL wouldn't
give up without a word.

00:09:50.285 --> 00:09:52.842
And a week later, we
found that Messenger

00:09:52.842 --> 00:09:53.800
had been blocked again.

00:09:53.800 --> 00:09:55.680
But this time was different.

00:09:55.680 --> 00:09:59.470
The AOL server was sending a
huge chunk of new gobbledygook

00:09:59.470 --> 00:10:00.910
that I could not understand.

00:10:00.910 --> 00:10:02.830
And it looked like this.

00:10:02.830 --> 00:10:06.850
The first couple lines are the
standard AOL protocol header,

00:10:06.850 --> 00:10:08.850
the 2A02779C.

00:10:08.850 --> 00:10:12.000
This is all fairly
standard stuff.

00:10:12.000 --> 00:10:17.530
But from these 90, 90, 90, 90,
onward, it was incomprehensible

00:10:17.530 --> 00:10:21.417
and didn't bear any relation
to anything the AOL service had

00:10:21.417 --> 00:10:22.500
sent their client or ours.

00:10:22.500 --> 00:10:24.900
The vast expanse of
double zeros in the middle

00:10:24.900 --> 00:10:27.870
was also mysterious,
since a bunch of zeros

00:10:27.870 --> 00:10:30.140
couldn't contain much meaning.

00:10:30.140 --> 00:10:31.180
Our client ignored it.

00:10:31.180 --> 00:10:33.690
But the AOL client responded
to this gobbledygook

00:10:33.690 --> 00:10:35.700
with a shorter version
of the same gobbledygook.

00:10:35.700 --> 00:10:37.060
I didn't know what it was.

00:10:37.060 --> 00:10:38.812
And it was maddening.

00:10:38.812 --> 00:10:40.410
After staring at
it for half a day,

00:10:40.410 --> 00:10:42.690
I went over to Jonathan,
a brilliant server

00:10:42.690 --> 00:10:44.747
engineer on our team, and
asked what he thought.

00:10:44.747 --> 00:10:46.830
And he looked at it for a
few minutes and he said,

00:10:46.830 --> 00:10:48.390
this is code.

00:10:48.390 --> 00:10:51.514
Specifically, well, that's code.

00:10:51.514 --> 00:10:52.680
Actually, most of it's code.

00:10:52.680 --> 00:10:55.900
But the most important part is
down here as you might guess.

00:10:55.900 --> 00:10:58.600
It was actual x86 assembly code.

00:10:58.600 --> 00:11:00.480
The repeated 90s
had tipped him off

00:11:00.480 --> 00:11:03.510
because they signify
a no-op instruction

00:11:03.510 --> 00:11:05.400
x86 assembler
telling the processor

00:11:05.400 --> 00:11:07.440
to do nothing for one cycle.

00:11:07.440 --> 00:11:09.000
So the pieces came together.

00:11:09.000 --> 00:11:12.640
Normally, protocol messages
read as data, not as code.

00:11:12.640 --> 00:11:16.320
But AOL's client had
a security bug in it.

00:11:16.320 --> 00:11:19.370
It had a buffer overflow in it.

00:11:19.370 --> 00:11:21.120
And, actually, let me
ask, how many people

00:11:21.120 --> 00:11:22.380
know what a buffer overflow is?

00:11:22.380 --> 00:11:23.920
I'm going to skip
over, oh, everyone.

00:11:23.920 --> 00:11:25.170
We're going to skip over that.

00:11:25.170 --> 00:11:27.240
Actually, for all the
viewers in TV land,

00:11:27.240 --> 00:11:31.170
it basically means is
that you can run over

00:11:31.170 --> 00:11:37.050
the edge of an
assigned spot in memory

00:11:37.050 --> 00:11:41.350
and overwrite the program
code with whatever you want.

00:11:41.350 --> 00:11:45.000
So they were overwriting
it with x86 assembler.

00:11:45.000 --> 00:11:50.550
And they were controlling the
function of the AOL client.

00:11:50.550 --> 00:11:54.780
It's a huge security hole.

00:11:54.780 --> 00:11:57.240
And AOL knew about this
bug in their programming.

00:11:57.240 --> 00:11:58.780
And now they were exploiting it.

00:11:58.780 --> 00:12:01.650
The double zeros were filling up
space in the program's buffer.

00:12:01.650 --> 00:12:03.240
And once it hit the
end of the buffer,

00:12:03.240 --> 00:12:05.820
it overwrote the executable
code with the remainder

00:12:05.820 --> 00:12:08.340
of the protocol message.

00:12:08.340 --> 00:12:11.280
This is the new code
which caused the client

00:12:11.280 --> 00:12:15.060
to look up a particular
configurable address in memory

00:12:15.060 --> 00:12:16.976
and send it back to the server.

00:12:16.976 --> 00:12:19.170
And this was tricky
and much trickier

00:12:19.170 --> 00:12:21.030
than anything
they've done so far.

00:12:21.030 --> 00:12:23.850
And it was a bit outside
the realm of fair play,

00:12:23.850 --> 00:12:27.360
hacking into their own client
using an unfixed security

00:12:27.360 --> 00:12:30.550
hole, a hole that our
client did not possess.

00:12:30.550 --> 00:12:33.660
It was a "Rommel, you
magnificent bastard" moment.

00:12:33.660 --> 00:12:36.000
And I was out of my depth.

00:12:36.000 --> 00:12:37.939
Someone else at Microsoft--

00:12:37.939 --> 00:12:40.230
I never found out who-- told
the press about the buffer

00:12:40.230 --> 00:12:42.540
overflow, figuring that if
people knew that the AOL

00:12:42.540 --> 00:12:45.150
client had a huge
security hole in it,

00:12:45.150 --> 00:12:47.100
AOL would be forced
to patch their client

00:12:47.100 --> 00:12:49.660
and would no longer
be able to exploit it.

00:12:49.660 --> 00:12:52.650
So according to the security
expert Richard M. Smith,

00:12:52.650 --> 00:12:55.560
a certain Phil Bucking
of Bucking Consulting

00:12:55.560 --> 00:12:57.810
sent him an email,
alerting him to the buffer

00:12:57.810 --> 00:12:59.820
overflow in the AOL client.

00:12:59.820 --> 00:13:02.316
"Dear Mr. Smith,
I am a developer

00:13:02.316 --> 00:13:04.440
who has been working on a
revolutionary new instant

00:13:04.440 --> 00:13:06.870
messaging client that should
be released later this year.

00:13:06.870 --> 00:13:08.850
Because of that, I
followed with interest

00:13:08.850 --> 00:13:10.710
the battle between
AOL and Microsoft

00:13:10.710 --> 00:13:13.110
and have been trying to
understand exactly what AOL

00:13:13.110 --> 00:13:15.900
is doing to block
Microsoft and how Microsoft

00:13:15.900 --> 00:13:17.700
is getting around the blocks.

00:13:17.700 --> 00:13:20.250
Up until very recently, it's
been pretty standard stuff.

00:13:20.250 --> 00:13:23.500
But now I fear AOL
has gone too far.

00:13:23.500 --> 00:13:26.430
It appears that the AIM client
has a buffer overflow bug.

00:13:26.430 --> 00:13:28.620
By itself, this may not
be the end of the world

00:13:28.620 --> 00:13:30.962
as Microsoft has
surely had its share."

00:13:30.962 --> 00:13:35.690
[LAUGHTER] Yes, yes.

00:13:35.690 --> 00:13:39.480
"But AOL is now exploiting
their own buffer overflow bug

00:13:39.480 --> 00:13:44.510
to help its efforts to block
MSN Instant Messenger."

00:13:44.510 --> 00:13:47.970
So it's a bit
ham-fisted, I think.

00:13:47.970 --> 00:13:49.980
The developer of a
revolutionary new app

00:13:49.980 --> 00:13:51.990
takes sides in the
Microsoft-AOL war

00:13:51.990 --> 00:13:53.850
without promoting his own app?

00:13:53.850 --> 00:13:57.630
The email also includes
this actual trace.

00:13:57.630 --> 00:13:59.460
This is from the
email, because I

00:13:59.460 --> 00:14:01.590
don't have my notes from
it anymore, because those

00:14:01.590 --> 00:14:02.410
were confidential.

00:14:02.410 --> 00:14:04.390
But I can still have that.

00:14:04.390 --> 00:14:07.140
And if Phil Bucking's
text and his name

00:14:07.140 --> 00:14:09.390
weren't suspicious
enough, he'd also

00:14:09.390 --> 00:14:13.020
sent the message from one
of Microsoft's computers

00:14:13.020 --> 00:14:13.910
at a Microsoft IP.

00:14:13.910 --> 00:14:14.560
[LAUGHTER]

00:14:14.560 --> 00:14:17.610
The IP address showed
up in the email headers.

00:14:17.610 --> 00:14:19.110
And Microsoft's
digital fingerprints

00:14:19.110 --> 00:14:21.140
were all over the email.

00:14:21.140 --> 00:14:23.380
Smith accused Microsoft
of sending the email,

00:14:23.380 --> 00:14:24.570
and Microsoft fessed up.

00:14:24.570 --> 00:14:27.330
The news story that emerged
covered Microsoft's attempt

00:14:27.330 --> 00:14:30.300
to bad-mouth AOL under a
fake identity, an easier sell

00:14:30.300 --> 00:14:32.670
than explaining the
buffer overflow.

00:14:32.670 --> 00:14:34.410
People on various
security forums

00:14:34.410 --> 00:14:36.540
ascertained that the
buffer overflow was real

00:14:36.540 --> 00:14:38.280
and invade further against AOL.

00:14:38.280 --> 00:14:40.500
But the press wasn't
paying attention.

00:14:40.500 --> 00:14:43.410
The buffer overflow persisted
into several later versions

00:14:43.410 --> 00:14:44.590
of AOL's client.

00:14:44.590 --> 00:14:47.160
AOL never admitted a
thing, and the press never

00:14:47.160 --> 00:14:48.790
did understand it.

00:14:48.790 --> 00:14:50.100
So we gave up.

00:14:50.100 --> 00:14:52.830
And I licked my wounds, and
I joined the server team.

00:14:52.830 --> 00:14:56.610
The larger lesson
of the messenger war

00:14:56.610 --> 00:14:58.980
was that the workings
of code were no longer

00:14:58.980 --> 00:15:01.080
a private matter known
only to those steeped

00:15:01.080 --> 00:15:02.100
in the law of computing.

00:15:02.100 --> 00:15:04.770
They were increasingly
becoming public affairs

00:15:04.770 --> 00:15:07.320
that impacted national
and even global events.

00:15:07.320 --> 00:15:09.960
And, you know, certainly
coming in the wake of Cambridge

00:15:09.960 --> 00:15:14.460
Analytica, it proved
more true than anything

00:15:14.460 --> 00:15:16.990
even when I read this.

00:15:16.990 --> 00:15:19.680
The chat wars were to me
a duel between a handful

00:15:19.680 --> 00:15:21.840
of people within two
gargantuan companies.

00:15:21.840 --> 00:15:25.680
And yet, they became a national
news story for a brief period.

00:15:25.680 --> 00:15:27.312
Looking back, it was
the first inkling

00:15:27.312 --> 00:15:28.770
I had that it wasn't
just computers

00:15:28.770 --> 00:15:31.600
that were permeating all our
lives but the code itself.

00:15:31.600 --> 00:15:34.420
And yet, few grasp code's
function and its impact,

00:15:34.420 --> 00:15:36.430
something that is
still true today.

00:15:36.430 --> 00:15:37.980
The ultimate outcome
of the conflict

00:15:37.980 --> 00:15:40.430
resulted from buffer overflow
whose existence was never

00:15:40.430 --> 00:15:44.540
agreed upon because neither
reporters nor the public

00:15:44.540 --> 00:15:45.680
understood it.

00:15:45.680 --> 00:15:47.690
So sometime after
I left Microsoft,

00:15:47.690 --> 00:15:50.970
I met one of the AOL engineers
who had worked against me.

00:15:50.970 --> 00:15:52.550
We had a huge laugh over it.

00:15:52.550 --> 00:15:54.770
And I complimented him on
the genius of the buffer

00:15:54.770 --> 00:15:58.300
overrun exploit, even
as I bemoaned my loss.

00:15:58.300 --> 00:16:00.860
It had been a great game,
I said, and he agreed.

00:16:00.860 --> 00:16:03.250
We were both dumbstruck
that we were still

00:16:03.250 --> 00:16:05.750
to a very small number of
people who knew the real story

00:16:05.750 --> 00:16:07.640
after all of these years.

00:16:07.640 --> 00:16:12.560
So that's the buffer
overflow story.

00:16:12.560 --> 00:16:18.530
The second section-- if you can
hold your questions to the end,

00:16:18.530 --> 00:16:22.130
I was going to read two
more short segments that

00:16:22.130 --> 00:16:23.780
relate to-- well,
the fact of the book

00:16:23.780 --> 00:16:25.800
goes all over the place.

00:16:25.800 --> 00:16:28.640
How many of you know "Dwarf
Fortress," by the way?

00:16:28.640 --> 00:16:29.430
Just a couple?

00:16:29.430 --> 00:16:31.290
OK, I'm not going to be speaking
about that today, although I

00:16:31.290 --> 00:16:32.990
did think about
talking about it.

00:16:32.990 --> 00:16:34.460
But I discussed
that in the book,

00:16:34.460 --> 00:16:37.580
because I think it's a good
example of how computers can

00:16:37.580 --> 00:16:39.900
and cannot model the world.

00:16:39.900 --> 00:16:44.300
So this is a section called
"Truthtellers and Liars."

00:16:44.300 --> 00:16:46.700
It begins with a
Charles Sanders Peirse

00:16:46.700 --> 00:16:50.750
quote, "All that logic warrants
is a hope and not a belief."

00:16:50.750 --> 00:16:52.820
So there is a type
of puzzle made

00:16:52.820 --> 00:16:55.460
most famous by the
logician Raymond Smullyan

00:16:55.460 --> 00:16:57.620
and by the movie
"Labyrinth" that involves

00:16:57.620 --> 00:16:59.750
liars and truthtellers.

00:16:59.750 --> 00:17:03.001
And how many of you know these
sorts of liar-truthteller logic

00:17:03.001 --> 00:17:03.500
puzzles?

00:17:03.500 --> 00:17:07.460
Yeah, OK, we'll
just skip over that.

00:17:07.460 --> 00:17:09.828
I'll just give you a variant
that I gave to my daughter.

00:17:09.828 --> 00:17:11.119
Let's say, we've got two doors.

00:17:11.119 --> 00:17:12.980
And behind one is a
huge amount of money,

00:17:12.980 --> 00:17:15.550
and behind the other is a shark.

00:17:15.550 --> 00:17:17.210
I decided that the
lady or the tiger

00:17:17.210 --> 00:17:21.240
was a bit of a relic
from an earlier era,

00:17:21.240 --> 00:17:23.300
so I changed it
to money or shark,

00:17:23.300 --> 00:17:26.200
which I thought was
very, very contemporary.

00:17:26.200 --> 00:17:28.830
OK, so the writing on the doors;
on door one, "The shark is

00:17:28.830 --> 00:17:31.481
in here;" door two,
"Both doors are lying."

00:17:31.481 --> 00:17:33.230
Well, door two must
be lying, because it's

00:17:33.230 --> 00:17:35.180
impossible to truthfully
say that you're a liar,

00:17:35.180 --> 00:17:36.980
so door one must be
true, or else door two

00:17:36.980 --> 00:17:38.030
would be telling the truth.

00:17:38.030 --> 00:17:39.821
The shark is behind
door one, and the money

00:17:39.821 --> 00:17:41.240
is behind door two.

00:17:41.240 --> 00:17:44.210
I compulsively worked through
hundreds of these as a kid.

00:17:44.210 --> 00:17:47.450
And I was fortunate my mother
stumbled on Smullyan's book

00:17:47.450 --> 00:17:48.650
"Alice in Puzzle-land."

00:17:48.650 --> 00:17:51.770
How many of you read
"Alice in Puzzle-land?"

00:17:51.770 --> 00:17:54.197
I was going to say, there's
got to be at least a couple.

00:17:54.197 --> 00:17:56.780
And that became my introduction
to the field of Boolean logic,

00:17:56.780 --> 00:18:00.730
in liar-truthteller puzzles
and logical paradoxes.

00:18:00.730 --> 00:18:03.920
Smullyan's use of Lewis Carroll
suited the truthteller puzzles

00:18:03.920 --> 00:18:08.457
since, you know, Carroll
had been a logician himself.

00:18:08.457 --> 00:18:10.040
And some of the
puzzles in these books

00:18:10.040 --> 00:18:12.290
grew extraordinarily
ornate, requiring

00:18:12.290 --> 00:18:14.205
multiple levels of inference.

00:18:14.205 --> 00:18:16.580
Sometimes they didn't tell
you what one or another person

00:18:16.580 --> 00:18:17.079
had said.

00:18:17.079 --> 00:18:18.770
Sometimes "yes" and
"no" were replaced

00:18:18.770 --> 00:18:21.920
with nonsense words like "bal"
and "da" that meant yes or no,

00:18:21.920 --> 00:18:23.200
but you didn't know which.

00:18:23.200 --> 00:18:25.100
There were even
abstruse puzzles that

00:18:25.100 --> 00:18:28.100
attempted to explain Kurt
Godel's Incompleteness Theorem,

00:18:28.100 --> 00:18:32.890
but it was above my
head at that age.

00:18:32.890 --> 00:18:35.550
But one puzzle
genuinely irritated me.

00:18:35.550 --> 00:18:37.530
And this is a simplified
version of it.

00:18:37.530 --> 00:18:40.520
So a man is trying to figure
out which of two caskets

00:18:40.520 --> 00:18:41.980
contain a portrait.

00:18:41.980 --> 00:18:45.000
On the first portrait, we have,
"The portrait is not in here."

00:18:45.000 --> 00:18:48.680
And the second casket said,
"Exactly one of these caskets

00:18:48.680 --> 00:18:49.680
is telling the truth."

00:18:49.680 --> 00:18:50.831
So where's the portrait?

00:18:50.831 --> 00:18:53.330
Well, whether or not the second
casket is telling the truth,

00:18:53.330 --> 00:18:57.260
the first casket must
not be, because it says,

00:18:57.260 --> 00:18:59.030
"The portrait is not in here."

00:18:59.030 --> 00:19:00.590
Either the second
casket is true,

00:19:00.590 --> 00:19:02.990
and the first casket
is therefore false.

00:19:02.990 --> 00:19:06.050
Or the second casket is false,
and thus the first casket

00:19:06.050 --> 00:19:08.090
must be false as well,
or else the second casket

00:19:08.090 --> 00:19:09.215
would be telling the truth.

00:19:09.215 --> 00:19:11.360
In the puzzle, the man
also figures the portrait

00:19:11.360 --> 00:19:12.560
is in the first casket.

00:19:12.560 --> 00:19:14.840
He opens it up
and finds nothing.

00:19:14.840 --> 00:19:16.340
The portrait's in
the second casket.

00:19:16.340 --> 00:19:17.840
He is utterly baffled.

00:19:17.840 --> 00:19:20.360
And so was I. And the
answer seemed indisputable

00:19:20.360 --> 00:19:22.040
in this very simple puzzle.

00:19:22.040 --> 00:19:25.190
So here's what Smullyan
wrote as an explanation.

00:19:25.190 --> 00:19:27.830
"Without any information given
about the truth or falsity

00:19:27.830 --> 00:19:30.170
of any of these sentences,
nor any information given

00:19:30.170 --> 00:19:32.036
about the relation of
their truth values,

00:19:32.036 --> 00:19:33.410
the sentences
could say anything,

00:19:33.410 --> 00:19:34.804
and the object
could be anywhere.

00:19:34.804 --> 00:19:36.720
Good heavens, I can take
any number of caskets

00:19:36.720 --> 00:19:38.330
that I please and put
an object in one of them

00:19:38.330 --> 00:19:40.490
and then write any inscriptions
at all on the lids,

00:19:40.490 --> 00:19:43.090
and these sentences won't
convey any information."

00:19:43.090 --> 00:19:44.360
I felt cheated.

00:19:44.360 --> 00:19:46.700
I felt that Smullyan had
made an implicit promise

00:19:46.700 --> 00:19:49.890
that he would be providing
logic puzzles that made sense.

00:19:49.890 --> 00:19:53.060
But I grudgingly observed
the other puzzles explicitly

00:19:53.060 --> 00:19:55.110
claimed that the rules
were being obeyed.

00:19:55.110 --> 00:19:57.890
And in this puzzle, there
was no such guarantee.

00:19:57.890 --> 00:19:59.990
The lesson was that
truth and falsity

00:19:59.990 --> 00:20:02.780
are not absolute but
relative to a context.

00:20:02.780 --> 00:20:06.230
Outside that context, statements
lose sense of meaning.

00:20:06.230 --> 00:20:08.450
Without the guarantee that
rules are being followed,

00:20:08.450 --> 00:20:10.580
we can never be sure that
our reasoning is valid.

00:20:10.580 --> 00:20:13.280
And nowhere is that more
true than in the logical

00:20:13.280 --> 00:20:16.880
and contextually isolated
world of computers.

00:20:16.880 --> 00:20:24.570
So from there, I go on to
talk about bits themselves.

00:20:24.570 --> 00:20:32.180
Bits are commonly represented
by the degree of voltage on--

00:20:32.180 --> 00:20:33.510
in transistor.

00:20:33.510 --> 00:20:36.530
And there's nothing true
or false on circuit boards

00:20:36.530 --> 00:20:39.580
containing transistors-- the
binaries between the voltage

00:20:39.580 --> 00:20:41.160
being on or off.

00:20:41.160 --> 00:20:45.345
Off isn't actually zero
as I made sure to say.

00:20:45.345 --> 00:20:48.550
And the binary isn't between
true or false or even 0 and 1.

00:20:48.550 --> 00:20:51.190
No one is actually interested
in whether gates output

00:20:51.190 --> 00:20:53.110
a voltage signal
except in as much

00:20:53.110 --> 00:20:55.800
as that signal represents
something else.

00:20:55.800 --> 00:20:57.970
And what such signals
represent in a computer

00:20:57.970 --> 00:21:00.760
is an abstract notion of
logical truth and falsehood,

00:21:00.760 --> 00:21:03.280
which is a notion imposed by us.

00:21:03.280 --> 00:21:05.230
Truth and falsehood
are conceptions

00:21:05.230 --> 00:21:07.630
that we apply to the presence
or absence of a signal

00:21:07.630 --> 00:21:10.640
at a particular point
on a circuit board.

00:21:10.640 --> 00:21:12.610
The binary
representation of truth

00:21:12.610 --> 00:21:14.800
is so ubiquitous
that we chronically

00:21:14.800 --> 00:21:18.460
[? complate ?] logical true
false and computational 1 0,

00:21:18.460 --> 00:21:20.190
on off binaries.

00:21:20.190 --> 00:21:22.900
A programming language permits
me to have a Boolean variable.

00:21:22.900 --> 00:21:24.460
Let's call it is
this thing on, which

00:21:24.460 --> 00:21:26.200
can be either true or false.

00:21:26.200 --> 00:21:28.930
And the simplest representation
and most common representation

00:21:28.930 --> 00:21:31.510
would be to use 0 for
false and 1 for true.

00:21:31.510 --> 00:21:33.970
But what if with this
numerical representation

00:21:33.970 --> 00:21:37.257
we run across a 2 or some
other number that's not 0 or 1?

00:21:37.257 --> 00:21:39.340
We could declare those
numbers to be meaningless--

00:21:39.340 --> 00:21:40.367
neither true nor false.

00:21:40.367 --> 00:21:42.700
But we don't want a ternary
logic in which there are not

00:21:42.700 --> 00:21:43.910
two, but three options--

00:21:43.910 --> 00:21:45.340
true, false, and meaningless.

00:21:45.340 --> 00:21:47.560
So in C the convention
is that 0 is false.

00:21:47.560 --> 00:21:50.380
And any other number is true.

00:21:50.380 --> 00:21:52.660
This representation appeals
to our common convention

00:21:52.660 --> 00:21:54.670
of equating truth
with existence.

00:21:54.670 --> 00:21:57.890
Falsehood is nothing--
absence, emptiness, is zero.

00:21:57.890 --> 00:21:59.980
Truth is presence of
validity existence.

00:21:59.980 --> 00:22:03.250
Anything other than zero
even a negative number--

00:22:03.250 --> 00:22:05.680
for those of you who
use Microsoft H results

00:22:05.680 --> 00:22:07.750
you know that it's
reversed in that way.

00:22:07.750 --> 00:22:12.610
And 0 is actually the
standard success result--

00:22:12.610 --> 00:22:15.010
something that
caused a lot of bugs

00:22:15.010 --> 00:22:19.780
when people just
used to not sign on H

00:22:19.780 --> 00:22:22.760
results thinking that
they were binary results.

00:22:22.760 --> 00:22:24.675
A programmer is--
and I include myself

00:22:24.675 --> 00:22:26.050
in this-- is
conditioned to treat

00:22:26.050 --> 00:22:29.590
true and false as synonyms
for 1 and 0 respectively.

00:22:29.590 --> 00:22:31.780
True and false become
the two possible values

00:22:31.780 --> 00:22:35.710
for a single bit in
a two bit system.

00:22:35.710 --> 00:22:38.114
It is two value system.

00:22:38.114 --> 00:22:38.870
[LAUGHTER]

00:22:38.870 --> 00:22:40.930
These truths and
falsehoods remain a purely

00:22:40.930 --> 00:22:42.670
formal convention
even though the words

00:22:42.670 --> 00:22:44.840
contain metaphysical
weight within them.

00:22:44.840 --> 00:22:46.540
If I write God
exists equals true,

00:22:46.540 --> 00:22:48.777
that obviously doesn't
cause God to exist.

00:22:48.777 --> 00:22:50.860
Nor does it cause the
computer to think or believe

00:22:50.860 --> 00:22:51.970
that God exists.

00:22:51.970 --> 00:22:53.860
All it does is set a
signal somewhere deep

00:22:53.860 --> 00:22:56.260
in the recesses of
a computer's memory.

00:22:56.260 --> 00:22:57.910
That line of code,
however, suggests

00:22:57.910 --> 00:23:00.685
more than just the changing
of signal on a circuit board.

00:23:00.685 --> 00:23:03.320
Any meaning we assign
to true and false

00:23:03.320 --> 00:23:06.830
besides the signals being
on or off is interpretation.

00:23:06.830 --> 00:23:09.880
If I say God exists, I'm making
a claim about the real world.

00:23:09.880 --> 00:23:12.640
When a program contains a
statement God exists equal one,

00:23:12.640 --> 00:23:16.270
it merely indicates the
alteration of a signal.

00:23:16.270 --> 00:23:18.850
So computers don't
understand the difference

00:23:18.850 --> 00:23:19.870
between true and false.

00:23:19.870 --> 00:23:22.195
Nor do they understand
what the concepts mean.

00:23:22.195 --> 00:23:25.570
And if a computer is to gain any
grasp on truth as we understand

00:23:25.570 --> 00:23:29.530
it, it will have to be someplace
other than in its bits.

00:23:29.530 --> 00:23:33.010
And another quote
from Thomas Pynchon--

00:23:33.010 --> 00:23:36.034
"Who claims truth,
truth abandons."

00:23:36.034 --> 00:23:39.210
And there's a little
historical context.

00:23:39.210 --> 00:23:40.990
The history of logic
has long wrestled

00:23:40.990 --> 00:23:43.780
with the problem of getting
that true to mean more than one

00:23:43.780 --> 00:23:45.250
or on--

00:23:45.250 --> 00:23:48.580
the problem of getting true to
say something about the world.

00:23:48.580 --> 00:23:50.980
The difficulty started
long before computers.

00:23:50.980 --> 00:23:52.420
We may think that
we can patently

00:23:52.420 --> 00:23:54.880
tell the difference between
a true and a false statement.

00:23:54.880 --> 00:23:57.460
But outside of logic puzzles
pinning down this distinction

00:23:57.460 --> 00:23:59.740
proves horrendously
vexing to the point

00:23:59.740 --> 00:24:02.920
that both Western philosophers
like Sextus Empiricus

00:24:02.920 --> 00:24:05.410
and Eastern philosophers
like Nagarjuna

00:24:05.410 --> 00:24:08.230
question whether the truth
of anything could be known.

00:24:08.230 --> 00:24:11.230
These concerns, which might seem
like philosophical navel gazing

00:24:11.230 --> 00:24:13.450
became far more urgent
once formal logic

00:24:13.450 --> 00:24:14.620
entered the picture.

00:24:14.620 --> 00:24:17.260
The great logician
Alfred Tarski,

00:24:17.260 --> 00:24:20.400
an influence on computer science
and artificial intelligence,

00:24:20.400 --> 00:24:23.080
coined Convention T
as a minimal criterion

00:24:23.080 --> 00:24:24.857
for the truth of the statement.

00:24:24.857 --> 00:24:26.440
Here are two examples
of Convention T.

00:24:26.440 --> 00:24:29.200
Actually how many of
you know convention T?

00:24:29.200 --> 00:24:29.910
Not too many.

00:24:29.910 --> 00:24:30.409
OK.

00:24:30.409 --> 00:24:31.660
Logic's not in these days.

00:24:31.660 --> 00:24:33.618
All it is is you put a
sentence in quotes like,

00:24:33.618 --> 00:24:34.400
"The sky is blue."

00:24:34.400 --> 00:24:37.960
The sky is blue is true if
and only if the sky is blue.

00:24:37.960 --> 00:24:41.880
I am a jelly donut is true if
and only if I am a jelly donut.

00:24:41.880 --> 00:24:44.200
And a great deal of
philosophical ink

00:24:44.200 --> 00:24:45.760
has been spilled
on Convention T.

00:24:45.760 --> 00:24:48.460
But I think most people will
agree that this criterion is

00:24:48.460 --> 00:24:51.190
not especially helpful as a
practical guide to determining

00:24:51.190 --> 00:24:52.730
the truth of a statement.

00:24:52.730 --> 00:24:56.640
And yet we may even despair at
how little progress Convention

00:24:56.640 --> 00:25:01.060
T seems to make over Aristotle's
definition of over 2000

00:25:01.060 --> 00:25:01.990
years ago.

00:25:01.990 --> 00:25:03.490
To say of what it is--

00:25:03.490 --> 00:25:07.880
to say of what is that it is
not or of what is not that it is

00:25:07.880 --> 00:25:08.990
is false.

00:25:08.990 --> 00:25:11.740
While to say of what
it is that it is

00:25:11.740 --> 00:25:16.050
and of what is not
that it is not is true.

00:25:16.050 --> 00:25:16.850
Not so helpful.

00:25:16.850 --> 00:25:17.350
OK.

00:25:17.350 --> 00:25:18.330
Yeah.

00:25:18.330 --> 00:25:19.980
But whatever truth
may be, we can

00:25:19.980 --> 00:25:22.320
conclude that in order to
interact well with the world,

00:25:22.320 --> 00:25:24.630
computers must be
able to distinguish

00:25:24.630 --> 00:25:27.570
between true and false in
the same way as humans do.

00:25:27.570 --> 00:25:30.750
"The inadequacies of
logicians' attempts

00:25:30.750 --> 00:25:34.410
to collapse the difference
between a logical truth

00:25:34.410 --> 00:25:37.140
and a worldly truth have
been made all too clear

00:25:37.140 --> 00:25:38.370
in the computing age.

00:25:38.370 --> 00:25:41.610
The mathematician and
phenomenologist Gian-Carlo Rota

00:25:41.610 --> 00:25:43.410
put this bluntly.

00:25:43.410 --> 00:25:45.450
"Mathematicians are
therefore mystified

00:25:45.450 --> 00:25:47.370
by the spectacle of
philosophers pretending

00:25:47.370 --> 00:25:49.890
to re-inject philosophical
sense into the language

00:25:49.890 --> 00:25:51.370
of mathematical logic.

00:25:51.370 --> 00:25:53.340
The fake philosophical
terminology

00:25:53.340 --> 00:25:55.770
of mathematical logic
has misled philosophers

00:25:55.770 --> 00:25:57.570
into believing that
mathematical logic

00:25:57.570 --> 00:26:00.120
deals with the truth in
the philosophical sense.

00:26:00.120 --> 00:26:01.320
But this is a mistake.

00:26:01.320 --> 00:26:03.390
Mathematical logic
deals not with the truth

00:26:03.390 --> 00:26:05.160
but only with the game of truth.

00:26:05.160 --> 00:26:07.440
The snobbish symbol
dropping found nowadays

00:26:07.440 --> 00:26:09.600
in philosophical
papers raises eyebrows

00:26:09.600 --> 00:26:11.490
among mathematicians
like someone

00:26:11.490 --> 00:26:15.386
paying his grocery bill
with Monopoly money."

00:26:15.386 --> 00:26:18.180
Rota here echoes Plato's,
who was one of the first

00:26:18.180 --> 00:26:20.070
to find that truth as
a practical matter--

00:26:20.070 --> 00:26:25.515
a matter of action rather than
a pure theoretical abstraction.

00:26:25.515 --> 00:26:27.630
And Paul Friedlander's summary--

00:26:27.630 --> 00:26:31.140
"Truth in Plato's system is
always both reality of being

00:26:31.140 --> 00:26:34.410
and correctness of
apprehension and assertion."

00:26:34.410 --> 00:26:36.300
Or in William James's words--

00:26:36.300 --> 00:26:37.770
"Truth happens to an idea.

00:26:37.770 --> 00:26:40.560
It becomes true-- is
made true by events.

00:26:40.560 --> 00:26:43.290
The troublesome gap is not
between logic and language,

00:26:43.290 --> 00:26:44.880
between logic and reality.

00:26:44.880 --> 00:26:48.494
Symbols and proofs cannot
close that gap on their own."

00:26:48.494 --> 00:26:50.600
