than arguments per se.

00:34:39.000 --> 00:34:42.130
And so crafting
a narrative story

00:34:42.130 --> 00:34:46.199
that illustrates a point in a
more concrete and visceral way

00:34:46.199 --> 00:34:50.100
can actually be more effective
than a deductive argument

00:34:50.100 --> 00:34:52.530
in which you argue
from first principles,

00:34:52.530 --> 00:34:55.860
because there's usually some
assumption made in there

00:34:55.860 --> 00:34:58.580
or some prior if
you're a Bayesian

00:34:58.580 --> 00:35:03.170
that if you don't agree on,
you'll just say no, no, no,

00:35:03.170 --> 00:35:04.350
this is completely invalid.

00:35:04.350 --> 00:35:05.475
I'm not going to follow it.

00:35:05.475 --> 00:35:07.590
But you know, you got a story.

00:35:07.590 --> 00:35:12.230
And the thread of narrative
is carrying you through.

00:35:12.230 --> 00:35:15.460
That's sort of my
thinking about it.

00:35:15.460 --> 00:35:16.190
Hi.

00:35:16.190 --> 00:35:17.230
AUDIENCE: I'm just
wondering if I

00:35:17.230 --> 00:35:19.240
could ask you about your
process writing this book.

00:35:19.240 --> 00:35:21.340
I know you said in the Q&amp;A
how, like, you ended up

00:35:21.340 --> 00:35:23.560
finding narrative themes
that you might not

00:35:23.560 --> 00:35:24.880
have intended initially.

00:35:24.880 --> 00:35:26.710
Like, how was the
process in general?

00:35:26.710 --> 00:35:27.835
DAVID AUERBACH: Oh, my God.

00:35:27.835 --> 00:35:29.601
You read the Q&amp;A. Oh, my God.

00:35:29.601 --> 00:35:30.100
OK.

00:35:30.100 --> 00:35:33.100
Well, oh, boy.

00:35:33.100 --> 00:35:37.895
Let me say something
that I haven't already.

00:35:37.895 --> 00:35:41.570
The process-- well,
actually to return

00:35:41.570 --> 00:35:43.760
to the previous
question, I did start off

00:35:43.760 --> 00:35:45.650
by writing some pretty
theoretical stuff.

00:35:45.650 --> 00:35:49.110
And I think my editor sort of
reacted with horror saying--

00:35:49.110 --> 00:35:49.985
there was an entire--

00:35:49.985 --> 00:35:51.476
[LAUGHTER]

00:35:51.476 --> 00:35:53.030
There was an entire--

00:35:53.030 --> 00:35:55.610
back in the day I did
compiler research.

00:35:55.610 --> 00:35:57.920
I loved working on
compilers, because it

00:35:57.920 --> 00:36:00.320
was like-- it's like, oh,
it puts everything together.

00:36:00.320 --> 00:36:05.510
And I had a chapter on
compilers and compilers

00:36:05.510 --> 00:36:08.660
as illustrating the structure
of abstraction layers

00:36:08.660 --> 00:36:09.740
and computers.

00:36:09.740 --> 00:36:11.730
That chapter got cut.

00:36:11.730 --> 00:36:15.080
And it got replaced with
a chapter on my daughter.

00:36:15.080 --> 00:36:16.030
[LAUGHTER]

00:36:16.030 --> 00:36:20.630
And you know, what can I say?

00:36:20.630 --> 00:36:22.680
Maybe it will go
into the next book.

00:36:22.680 --> 00:36:27.120
But so it was a matter
of approximation.

00:36:27.120 --> 00:36:29.580
And it was a way of--

00:36:29.580 --> 00:36:33.640
I had some existing
pieces that I'd written.

00:36:33.640 --> 00:36:35.960
There is one in particular
called the "The Stupidity

00:36:35.960 --> 00:36:41.351
of Computers" for n+1 that
I think did provide the germ

00:36:41.351 --> 00:36:41.850
for this.

00:36:41.850 --> 00:36:48.110
And what I set out wanting to
do was to write something that

00:36:48.110 --> 00:36:52.430
wasn't necessarily for
a technical audience

00:36:52.430 --> 00:36:54.530
although I tried
very hard to make it

00:36:54.530 --> 00:36:58.290
so that someone technical
would read it and say,

00:36:58.290 --> 00:37:01.730
OK, this person
speaks my language,

00:37:01.730 --> 00:37:05.810
because whenever I'd
written for various venues

00:37:05.810 --> 00:37:08.136
I would often speak to a
software engineer there.

00:37:08.136 --> 00:37:09.260
And they'd say, oh, my God.

00:37:09.260 --> 00:37:10.370
I'm so glad you're
writing for us.

00:37:10.370 --> 00:37:11.786
You actually
understand computers.

00:37:11.786 --> 00:37:15.990
And I-- this happened
enough that I was like, OK,

00:37:15.990 --> 00:37:20.210
there's a gap here in terms
of people do not want to read

00:37:20.210 --> 00:37:28.010
another abstract critique of
how the post-modern structure

00:37:28.010 --> 00:37:34.230
of computation is altering
the nature of subjectivity

00:37:34.230 --> 00:37:37.250
in the postmodern age-- you
know, something like that--

00:37:37.250 --> 00:37:41.810
you know, that being
able to talk about this

00:37:41.810 --> 00:37:45.890
in which the particulars of the
computer science matter is I

00:37:45.890 --> 00:37:50.270
think something that actually
is very useful and helpful.

00:37:50.270 --> 00:37:55.670
And so I wanted to
sort of communicate

00:37:55.670 --> 00:37:58.940
that toolset as well as
some greater reflections

00:37:58.940 --> 00:37:59.870
on that toolset--

00:37:59.870 --> 00:38:02.060
things that I didn't
know when I even--

00:38:02.060 --> 00:38:06.410
in college but sort of had come
to from thinking about them.

00:38:06.410 --> 00:38:10.950
I'll tell you I was a columnist
for Slate for some years.

00:38:10.950 --> 00:38:14.690
And one of these shockingly--
well, there were two columns--

00:38:14.690 --> 00:38:16.430
actually there
were three columns

00:38:16.430 --> 00:38:19.910
that I wrote that were
incredibly surprisingly

00:38:19.910 --> 00:38:20.420
popular.

00:38:20.420 --> 00:38:24.640
One was on the amazing
kids game Robot Odyssey.

00:38:24.640 --> 00:38:27.020
How many people here ever
played Robot Odyssey?

00:38:27.020 --> 00:38:30.760
The hardest computer
game-- it was--

00:38:30.760 --> 00:38:33.320
you had to use logic
gates to program robots.

00:38:33.320 --> 00:38:35.900
This was made for the
Apple II in, like, 1984.

00:38:35.900 --> 00:38:38.480
It is the hardest computer
game I ever played.

00:38:38.480 --> 00:38:40.610
I didn't solve it
until I was in college,

00:38:40.610 --> 00:38:46.760
because what it asks you to
do with logic gates is so damn

00:38:46.760 --> 00:38:47.740
abstract.

00:38:47.740 --> 00:38:50.060
And I didn't possess
those skills back then.

00:38:50.060 --> 00:38:51.480
That one was a huge hit.

00:38:51.480 --> 00:38:54.710
A piece on Roko's
basilisk was a huge hit,

00:38:54.710 --> 00:38:56.537
because everybody
loves Roko's basilisk.

00:38:56.537 --> 00:38:58.370
And if you don't know
about Roko's basilisk,

00:38:58.370 --> 00:38:59.800
you should look it up.

00:38:59.800 --> 00:39:03.350
And the third one was about
Wittgenstein and philosophy

00:39:03.350 --> 00:39:05.930
of language and how it
related to computer science

00:39:05.930 --> 00:39:08.540
and how it had helped me
understand some of the things

00:39:08.540 --> 00:39:10.420
I was talking about.

00:39:10.420 --> 00:39:14.510
And so in some ways,
those three pieces

00:39:14.510 --> 00:39:19.360
understanding that computers
were now touching everyday life

00:39:19.360 --> 00:39:21.920
and that the best way
of understanding this

00:39:21.920 --> 00:39:26.540
was to both have a grasp
of bits and the structures

00:39:26.540 --> 00:39:29.870
of computing, as well as the
larger picture of what they

00:39:29.870 --> 00:39:31.760
meant in terms of
everyday living

00:39:31.760 --> 00:39:34.400
was something that I
wanted to communicate.

00:39:34.400 --> 00:39:36.890
And then I thought I could
hopefully have something

00:39:36.890 --> 00:39:38.140
useful to contribute on.

00:39:38.140 --> 00:39:38.840
I don't know.

00:39:38.840 --> 00:39:40.470
Does that answer your question?

00:39:40.470 --> 00:39:41.967
Thanks for reading
the Q&amp;A. I think

00:39:41.967 --> 00:39:44.300
I also said that it was the
hardest thing I'd ever done.

00:39:44.300 --> 00:39:46.450
And I still agree with that.

00:39:46.450 --> 00:39:48.830
It was not-- writing is hard.

00:39:48.830 --> 00:39:51.054
I don't recommend it to
anyone who absolutely

00:39:51.054 --> 00:39:51.970
doesn't need to do it.

00:39:51.970 --> 00:39:54.397
[LAUGHTER]

00:39:54.397 --> 00:39:55.730
AUDIENCE: Hi, thanks for coming.

00:39:55.730 --> 00:39:57.180
I look forward to
reading the book.

00:39:57.180 --> 00:39:58.050
DAVID AUERBACH: Thank you.

00:39:58.050 --> 00:40:00.508
AUDIENCE: So I don't know if
you answered this in the book.

00:40:00.508 --> 00:40:03.710
But there's been a lot of talk
last few years about teaching

00:40:03.710 --> 00:40:05.900
computational thinking
to more and more people

00:40:05.900 --> 00:40:08.615
or more simplistically teaching
programming to everyone.

00:40:08.615 --> 00:40:12.180
And I'm curious what you think--
whether this is a good thing.

00:40:12.180 --> 00:40:14.952
Or is it being overhyped?

00:40:14.952 --> 00:40:16.910
DAVID AUERBACH: I mean,
I guess it can be both.

00:40:16.910 --> 00:40:17.844
There's always a hype.

00:40:17.844 --> 00:40:19.760
There's always hype
around something or other.

00:40:19.760 --> 00:40:21.343
It's like, you can
say to some extent,

00:40:21.343 --> 00:40:25.730
oh it's teaching kids about
big data and a good thing

00:40:25.730 --> 00:40:26.450
or overhyped.

00:40:26.450 --> 00:40:29.270
Well, yes, it's good to
know about those things.

00:40:29.270 --> 00:40:32.180
But the words big data
may make you think,

00:40:32.180 --> 00:40:34.490
oh, well, let's not
teach it like that.

00:40:34.490 --> 00:40:41.400
And I think everyone can
certainly benefit from knowing

00:40:41.400 --> 00:40:44.070
how code works just in the way
that I think they're going--

00:40:44.070 --> 00:40:47.850
people should-- can benefit from
knowing a bit about how machine

00:40:47.850 --> 00:40:50.760
learning models work and
how they can and can't--

00:40:50.760 --> 00:40:54.600
what they can and can't do.

00:40:54.600 --> 00:40:57.930
At the same time, you
know, marketing it

00:40:57.930 --> 00:41:02.370
as, oh, this is going to be
of practical usage to you

00:41:02.370 --> 00:41:04.287
and you should definitely
become a programmer

00:41:04.287 --> 00:41:06.370
or something like that I
don't think is necessary.

00:41:06.370 --> 00:41:10.050
I think that it would be better
to propose this as, yes, this

00:41:10.050 --> 00:41:13.200
is fundamental knowledge
in the same way

00:41:13.200 --> 00:41:16.920
that mathematics is logic--
having some base even

00:41:16.920 --> 00:41:20.250
theoretical appreciation
of what an algorithm is,

00:41:20.250 --> 00:41:22.110
how an algorithm can work.

00:41:22.110 --> 00:41:25.109
Maybe this is because I found
this stuff really interesting.

00:41:25.109 --> 00:41:25.650
I don't know.

00:41:25.650 --> 00:41:28.725
We recently picked up a
book for my seven-year-old--

00:41:28.725 --> 00:41:30.930
a mathematics book
for a 7-year-old

00:41:30.930 --> 00:41:33.467
that was recommended to
us by someone or other.

00:41:33.467 --> 00:41:35.550
And they said, yeah, yeah,
this is great for like,

00:41:35.550 --> 00:41:37.380
really getting
your kid into math.

00:41:37.380 --> 00:41:40.110
And it was written
in [? LaTeX. ?]

00:41:40.110 --> 00:41:42.222
And I said, OK, good sign.

00:41:42.222 --> 00:41:44.430
But I started reading the
problems, like, oh, my God.

00:41:44.430 --> 00:41:46.480
There's group theory
for seven-year-olds.

00:41:46.480 --> 00:41:48.920
I was like, this is insane.

00:41:48.920 --> 00:41:50.640
I was like, this
is very impressive.

00:41:50.640 --> 00:41:52.490
But I literally--

00:41:52.490 --> 00:41:56.400
I'm-- the number of kids
who can absorb this level

00:41:56.400 --> 00:41:58.934
of abstraction, because
it was like, OK, well,

00:41:58.934 --> 00:42:01.350
let's say you have beads on a
chain that alternate between

00:42:01.350 --> 00:42:04.860
these three types of beads,
what is the 493rd bead?

00:42:04.860 --> 00:42:08.060
I was like for a seven-year-old?

00:42:08.060 --> 00:42:10.380
It's like, all right.

00:42:10.380 --> 00:42:12.550
So I think it's a good thing.

00:42:12.550 --> 00:42:15.540
I think that unfortunately,
especially ed tech being

00:42:15.540 --> 00:42:18.000
the way that it
is, there's reason

00:42:18.000 --> 00:42:20.400
to worry whether the right
things are being taught,

00:42:20.400 --> 00:42:22.620
you know?

00:42:22.620 --> 00:42:24.990
If you just teach people
how to design a clock

00:42:24.990 --> 00:42:27.210
and put it up on a screen,
that's interesting.

00:42:27.210 --> 00:42:31.140
I mean, it will get you
some appreciation and use.

00:42:31.140 --> 00:42:35.370
But I think that
putting it into context

00:42:35.370 --> 00:42:38.400
can be useful as
well, just this--

00:42:38.400 --> 00:42:43.290
I mean, it would be as if you
only did like arithmetic word

00:42:43.290 --> 00:42:46.230
problems in your entire
time at school, you know,

00:42:46.230 --> 00:42:48.899
instead of going on to
algebra and calculus.

00:42:48.899 --> 00:42:49.440
I don't know.

00:42:49.440 --> 00:42:50.500
Does that answer your question?

00:42:50.500 --> 00:42:51.083
AUDIENCE: Yes.

00:42:51.083 --> 00:42:52.260
DAVID AUERBACH: OK.

00:42:52.260 --> 00:42:56.550
AUDIENCE: You mentioned
a [INAUDIBLE] Logo

00:42:56.550 --> 00:42:58.160
example before.

00:42:58.160 --> 00:42:59.870
