you think about

00:42:59.870 --> 00:43:03.930
like this educational
programming things--

00:43:03.930 --> 00:43:09.030
where we're going and what
would be the future of Logo

00:43:09.030 --> 00:43:09.990
we're teaching?

00:43:09.990 --> 00:43:11.198
DAVID AUERBACH: I don't know.

00:43:11.198 --> 00:43:12.360
I mean, I look at Scratch.

00:43:12.360 --> 00:43:14.250
And I have such mixed
feelings about it,

00:43:14.250 --> 00:43:17.130
because on the one
hand, it's great to have

00:43:17.130 --> 00:43:22.470
the notion of
imperative language

00:43:22.470 --> 00:43:26.430
and functional abstraction.

00:43:26.430 --> 00:43:28.830
But on the other hand,
it's like, they are talking

00:43:28.830 --> 00:43:30.440
about recursion, you know.

00:43:30.440 --> 00:43:41.910
Where are the-- that I feel like
to some extent there's some--

00:43:41.910 --> 00:43:44.100
I do feel that you
could introduce

00:43:44.100 --> 00:43:46.740
some of these concepts-- some
of the higher order concepts

00:43:46.740 --> 00:43:48.600
in a cool way earlier on.

00:43:48.600 --> 00:43:52.490
But at the same time I--

00:43:52.490 --> 00:43:55.440
you know, the fact that the
kids are doing them is good.

00:43:55.440 --> 00:43:58.840
And I mean I've seen
other computer games--

00:43:58.840 --> 00:44:00.540
I've seen other,
like, kids games

00:44:00.540 --> 00:44:04.530
that work on similar principles.

00:44:04.530 --> 00:44:13.522
But I think to some
extent, you know,

00:44:13.522 --> 00:44:15.980
it doesn't necessarily have to
take the form of programming

00:44:15.980 --> 00:44:19.790
per se as much as
it is a certain form

00:44:19.790 --> 00:44:21.750
of algorithmic abstraction.

00:44:21.750 --> 00:44:24.320
And it doesn't necessarily
require programming so much

00:44:24.320 --> 00:44:28.880
as learning the
nature of how data

00:44:28.880 --> 00:44:32.360
structures and certain
algorithms can fit together.

00:44:32.360 --> 00:44:35.510
And I'm saying that vaguely,
because I'm just thinking back

00:44:35.510 --> 00:44:39.500
to the various things I did
when I was a kid that gave me

00:44:39.500 --> 00:44:40.250
an appreciation.

00:44:40.250 --> 00:44:43.610
You know, I think Truth Teller
and Logic Polls are great

00:44:43.610 --> 00:44:45.790
as well.

00:44:45.790 --> 00:44:48.960
And there are probably other
forms of puzzles that I

00:44:48.960 --> 00:44:49.460
haven't--

00:44:52.020 --> 00:44:55.140
that I'd never have played
that would be great as well.

00:44:55.140 --> 00:44:56.970
And I think that--

00:44:56.970 --> 00:44:58.544
well, we're all here at Google.

00:44:58.544 --> 00:44:59.960
But if some of us
worked on trying

00:44:59.960 --> 00:45:01.376
to figure out what
those are, that

00:45:01.376 --> 00:45:04.230
would be wonderful, as well.

00:45:04.230 --> 00:45:06.050
There was a puzzle
game I played recently

00:45:06.050 --> 00:45:08.720
called Stephen's Sausage Roll.

00:45:08.720 --> 00:45:09.780
Does anyone know that?

00:45:09.780 --> 00:45:11.750
It is the hardest
puzzle game I've

00:45:11.750 --> 00:45:13.960
played in many, many years.

00:45:13.960 --> 00:45:21.470
And I felt it training my
brain quite well in terms of--

00:45:21.470 --> 00:45:22.700
I mean, it is--

00:45:22.700 --> 00:45:25.310
you can see how it was
very heavily influenced

00:45:25.310 --> 00:45:27.080
by abstract algebra.

00:45:27.080 --> 00:45:33.050
But it translates those
concepts into applications

00:45:33.050 --> 00:45:36.260
within this game so that
you aren't doing, you know,

00:45:36.260 --> 00:45:38.660
purely abstract exercises.

00:45:38.660 --> 00:45:42.030
But you're actually executing
in a vaguely algorithmic manner.

00:45:42.030 --> 00:45:45.370
So I hope there's
more of that honestly.

00:45:45.370 --> 00:45:50.090
I think there's a lot
of room for improvement.

00:45:50.090 --> 00:45:52.180
Certainly, you know, I look at--

00:45:52.180 --> 00:45:53.750
actually it's
interesting, you know.

00:45:53.750 --> 00:45:54.958
My daughter's learning chess.

00:45:54.958 --> 00:45:56.900
And I feel like in some
ways chess tutelage

00:45:56.900 --> 00:46:00.770
has been developed very
well, because the levels

00:46:00.770 --> 00:46:03.020
of abstraction you treat
[? and trust ?] sort of go up

00:46:03.020 --> 00:46:04.140
that ladder like that.

00:46:04.140 --> 00:46:08.390
And it's because you have
such an established context

00:46:08.390 --> 00:46:10.070
that it's helpful.

00:46:10.070 --> 00:46:12.950
So in some ways, I would
say that learning chess

00:46:12.950 --> 00:46:15.230
may actually be better for
you than learning Scratch.

00:46:15.230 --> 00:46:17.180
I don't know.

