DAVID AUERBACH: That's
because it's JavaScript.

00:46:55.738 --> 00:46:56.330
[LAUGHTER]

00:46:56.330 --> 00:47:01.550
Try Python at least,
you know, or APL.

00:47:01.550 --> 00:47:03.600
Maybe he'll like the cool
little, like, you know,

00:47:03.600 --> 00:47:04.280
the symbols.

00:47:04.280 --> 00:47:06.195
I don't know.

00:47:06.195 --> 00:47:07.061
[LAUGHTER]

00:47:07.061 --> 00:47:07.560
Sorry.

00:47:10.070 --> 00:47:12.320
If I had been introduced to
JavaScript when I was six,

00:47:12.320 --> 00:47:14.126
I probably wouldn't
be a programmer.

00:47:14.126 --> 00:47:20.960
So-- does someone else
have a question back there?

00:47:20.960 --> 00:47:25.891
Peter, you must have a question
and give me a hard time.

00:47:25.891 --> 00:47:27.890
AUDIENCE: --too much
weight on logic and reason?

00:47:27.890 --> 00:47:28.760
DAVID AUERBACH: Do I what?

00:47:28.760 --> 00:47:30.593
AUDIENCE: Worry that
you put too much weight

00:47:30.593 --> 00:47:31.669
on logic and reason.

00:47:31.669 --> 00:47:33.460
DAVID AUERBACH: Didn't
I just criticize it?

00:47:33.460 --> 00:47:39.920
AUDIENCE: Well, yes, but
there was a lot of philosophy

00:47:39.920 --> 00:47:41.150
and logic in there.

00:47:41.150 --> 00:47:44.120
I mean, the
background experience

00:47:44.120 --> 00:47:47.210
there is the discovery
that winning an argument

00:47:47.210 --> 00:47:48.230
doesn't make you right.

00:47:48.230 --> 00:47:48.880
DAVID AUERBACH: Yeah.

00:47:48.880 --> 00:47:49.570
AUDIENCE: So--

00:47:49.570 --> 00:47:51.020
DAVID AUERBACH: Well,
I mean, to some extent

00:47:51.020 --> 00:47:52.700
I was hoping to play
to this audience.

00:47:52.700 --> 00:47:56.860
I wouldn't have
read that section

00:47:56.860 --> 00:47:58.550
to an audience of lit majors.

00:47:58.550 --> 00:48:02.090
But this is presumably what
folks here do all the time.

00:48:02.090 --> 00:48:06.980
And you know, maybe software
engineers have changed.

00:48:06.980 --> 00:48:14.420
But I feel that the impulse to
quantify and regiment things

00:48:14.420 --> 00:48:18.230
logically is still pretty
strong amongst software

00:48:18.230 --> 00:48:22.170
engineers and other sorts
of engineers and scientists.

00:48:22.170 --> 00:48:25.200
And so I think it's
worth exploring.

00:48:25.200 --> 00:48:28.070
And I think that the
stuff I talk about still

00:48:28.070 --> 00:48:32.570
underpins a lot of arguments.

00:48:32.570 --> 00:48:33.380
I think it even--

00:48:33.380 --> 00:48:35.360
you know, if you look at--

00:48:35.360 --> 00:48:36.290
you can see it--

00:48:36.290 --> 00:48:40.550
I guess if I were talking to
an audience of statisticians,

00:48:40.550 --> 00:48:43.380
I'd probably be talking about
Bayesianism and frequentists.

00:48:43.380 --> 00:48:45.410
And you could come
up and ask me,

00:48:45.410 --> 00:48:47.930
do you think you place too
much emphasis on statistics?

00:48:47.930 --> 00:48:50.850
And it's like, well, you
know, it's everywhere.

00:48:50.850 --> 00:48:53.880
So the world may place
too much emphasis on it.

00:48:53.880 --> 00:48:54.380
But--

00:48:54.380 --> 00:48:55.850
AUDIENCE: Do you think software
engineers actually believe

00:48:55.850 --> 00:48:57.450
in truth in their programs?

00:48:57.450 --> 00:48:59.440
DAVID AUERBACH: No, no,
no, I mean, that's a--

00:48:59.440 --> 00:49:01.460
what do I think software
engineers believe?

00:49:01.460 --> 00:49:03.170
I think that software
engineers have

00:49:03.170 --> 00:49:08.840
a tendency towards reifying
contingent categories

00:49:08.840 --> 00:49:16.370
as literal and permanent.

00:49:16.370 --> 00:49:24.200
For example, these four
personality tests--

00:49:24.200 --> 00:49:26.150
maybe people don't like--

00:49:26.150 --> 00:49:27.860
maybe people don't
go for Myers Briggs.

00:49:27.860 --> 00:49:30.530
But you know apparently
we subject a lot of people

00:49:30.530 --> 00:49:33.170
to classifying people
into four colors--

00:49:33.170 --> 00:49:36.296
green, blue, gold, and orange.

00:49:36.296 --> 00:49:39.950
And apparently most people
turn out to be greens.

00:49:39.950 --> 00:49:43.850
So if this is something that
we all take seriously here

00:49:43.850 --> 00:49:45.800
at Google, I would say--

00:49:45.800 --> 00:49:47.800
well, I know you don't
take it seriously, Peter.

00:49:47.800 --> 00:49:51.875
But would you argue that most
people take it seriously here?

00:49:51.875 --> 00:49:52.845
AUDIENCE: I can't tell.

00:49:52.845 --> 00:49:53.636
DAVID AUERBACH: OK.

00:49:53.636 --> 00:49:55.399
My experience was that they do.

00:49:59.231 --> 00:50:03.040
AUDIENCE: It's easy
to do over weight

00:50:03.040 --> 00:50:05.092
what shows up on
weird mail threads

00:50:05.092 --> 00:50:06.550
or in fact, any
mail thread, right?

00:50:06.550 --> 00:50:07.540
DAVID AUERBACH: This
is just from talking--

00:50:07.540 --> 00:50:08.230
AUDIENCE: --what people believe.

00:50:08.230 --> 00:50:09.760
DAVID AUERBACH: This was
just talking to people.

00:50:09.760 --> 00:50:12.110
I mean, I didn't read mail
threads when I was back here.

00:50:12.110 --> 00:50:12.610
[LAUGHTER]

00:50:12.610 --> 00:50:13.290
--seemed healthy.

00:50:13.290 --> 00:50:15.310
AUDIENCE: Well, if this were
address a statistical group,

00:50:15.310 --> 00:50:17.830
we would argue about your
sampling procedures, right?

00:50:17.830 --> 00:50:18.220
DAVID AUERBACH: We could.

00:50:18.220 --> 00:50:20.200
But don't you think you're
putting too much emphasis

00:50:20.200 --> 00:50:20.783
on statistics?

00:50:20.783 --> 00:50:23.770
[LAUGHTER]

00:50:23.770 --> 00:50:26.940
AUDIENCE: No, I think that's
the only way to truth.

00:50:26.940 --> 00:50:31.210
DAVID AUERBACH: Well,
so there you go.

00:50:31.210 --> 00:50:37.150
Perhaps overweighing the logical
truth in that definition--

00:50:37.150 --> 00:50:39.645
AUDIENCE: I have what I think
is a very relevant question.

00:50:39.645 --> 00:50:41.020
I was wondering
if you could talk

00:50:41.020 --> 00:50:43.990
about what it's like to
write for and be criticized

00:50:43.990 --> 00:50:45.355
by programmers on the internet.

00:50:48.628 --> 00:50:51.250
DAVID AUERBACH: Yeah,
I mean, I'll be honest

00:50:51.250 --> 00:50:53.500
and say people were
actually really nice.

00:50:53.500 --> 00:50:55.020
I think-- and this is--

00:50:55.020 --> 00:50:59.670
it sort of reinforced that
a lot of the feedback was,

00:50:59.670 --> 00:51:00.400
oh, my God.

00:51:00.400 --> 00:51:03.520
Finally someone who
knows about coding.

00:51:03.520 --> 00:51:06.430
So I would say if
anything I was spoiled,

00:51:06.430 --> 00:51:10.270
because I think that there's
not a lot of technical knowledge

00:51:10.270 --> 00:51:13.870
on display at least in these
so-called popular press

00:51:13.870 --> 00:51:24.400
or you know that I wouldn't
say I've gotten a lot of flack.

00:51:24.400 --> 00:51:28.840
But in general, I
think that if anything,

00:51:28.840 --> 00:51:30.887
I detected that there was
a certain frustration.

00:51:30.887 --> 00:51:32.470
And I mean this is
frustration of sort

00:51:32.470 --> 00:51:33.970
of getting writ
large at this point,

00:51:33.970 --> 00:51:36.490
because you have a
larger cultural clash.

00:51:36.490 --> 00:51:37.990
And this is something
that I've seen

00:51:37.990 --> 00:51:41.200
being involved in like
the New York writing scene

00:51:41.200 --> 00:51:45.130
and how much resentment
or at least loathing there

00:51:45.130 --> 00:51:51.730
is towards the Silicon Valley
and tech people of all stripes.

00:51:51.730 --> 00:51:54.700
And this can extend to
an ontological critique

00:51:54.700 --> 00:51:57.370
that anyone in
programming must therefore

00:51:57.370 --> 00:52:02.230
be an awful evil positivist,
which again, yeah, Peter,

00:52:02.230 --> 00:52:02.830
you're right.

00:52:02.830 --> 00:52:03.460
They aren't.

00:52:03.460 --> 00:52:07.780
But you know, there
are lots of big names

00:52:07.780 --> 00:52:10.930
who speak for
technical companies who

00:52:10.930 --> 00:52:15.460
certainly qualify more on the
positivist side of things.

00:52:15.460 --> 00:52:21.610
And there's a lot of unjustified
anger towards them, which

00:52:21.610 --> 00:52:23.110
I think is based in ignorance.

00:52:23.110 --> 00:52:26.680
I also think that,
yes, the worldview

00:52:26.680 --> 00:52:29.380
could do with some intelligent
critiques rather than

00:52:29.380 --> 00:52:31.180
ignorant critiques
that just cause them

00:52:31.180 --> 00:52:36.850
to double down and think
that you know maybe we

00:52:36.850 --> 00:52:40.540
should go back to
Ayn Rand, because she

00:52:40.540 --> 00:52:41.530
was right after all.

00:52:47.279 --> 00:52:47.820
I don't know.

00:52:47.820 --> 00:52:51.940
Is that-- how's
that for an answer?

00:52:51.940 --> 00:52:54.680
I mean, it's a culture clash.

00:52:54.680 --> 00:52:57.010
It really is.

00:52:57.010 --> 00:52:59.740
But and I guess
the thing is is I

00:52:59.740 --> 00:53:01.870
have an affection for
both sides I suppose,

00:53:01.870 --> 00:53:06.310
as well as frustration with
perhaps closed mindedness

00:53:06.310 --> 00:53:13.062
that occurs of which I have my
own variants of it, you know.

00:53:13.062 --> 00:53:14.520
Am I going to sit
here and tell you

00:53:14.520 --> 00:53:15.960
that you should Jacques Derrida?

00:53:15.960 --> 00:53:17.185
Hell no.

00:53:17.185 --> 00:53:22.170
Am I going to tell you that
you should sit here and read--

00:53:22.170 --> 00:53:24.570
I don't know Denis Diderot?

00:53:24.570 --> 00:53:25.443
Yes.

00:53:25.443 --> 00:53:28.290
So you know, there's
stuff to be gained.

00:53:28.290 --> 00:53:30.210
But unfortunately
what rises to the top

00:53:30.210 --> 00:53:32.280
is not always the best stuff.

00:53:32.280 --> 00:53:34.830
AUDIENCE: You mention that
writing is very hard work.

00:53:34.830 --> 00:53:36.625
And you wouldn't
recommend it to anyone.

00:53:36.625 --> 00:53:39.240
So do you plan to
continue writing?

00:53:39.240 --> 00:53:41.686
And will it be on
a similar topic?

00:53:41.686 --> 00:53:43.310
DAVID AUERBACH: Yeah,
I have a problem.

00:53:43.310 --> 00:53:45.390
Yeah, I mean it's--

00:53:45.390 --> 00:53:47.610
you do it if you can't
do anything else.

00:53:47.610 --> 00:53:50.040
I mean there's a Thomas
Mann quote where he said,

00:53:50.040 --> 00:53:52.290
a writer is someone for
whom writing is harder

00:53:52.290 --> 00:53:53.800
than it is for anyone else.

00:53:53.800 --> 00:53:55.144
And I don't think--

00:53:55.144 --> 00:53:57.060
I don't know that that's
true for all writers.

00:53:57.060 --> 00:53:58.620
But it's certainly true for me.

00:53:58.620 --> 00:54:04.630
And I just-- it
scratches some itch.

00:54:04.630 --> 00:54:09.390
And you try to do it so that
you hopefully are serving

00:54:09.390 --> 00:54:11.070
some greater purpose with it.

00:54:11.070 --> 00:54:13.620
But that's the sort of
question that can make you

00:54:13.620 --> 00:54:15.610
very, very self-conscious
in a hurry.

00:54:15.610 --> 00:54:18.410
But I do plan to continue it.

00:54:18.410 --> 00:54:21.120
I'm writing a young
adult novel right

00:54:21.120 --> 00:54:23.340
now to get a complete
break from this,

00:54:23.340 --> 00:54:27.350
because I didn't want to
write about myself anymore.

00:54:27.350 --> 00:54:27.900
But yes.

00:54:27.900 --> 00:54:32.280
I have more to say
about computers.

00:54:32.280 --> 00:54:37.840
And hopefully, that'll be
in coming in the short term.

00:54:37.840 --> 00:54:40.051
AUDIENCE: What is short term?

00:54:40.051 --> 00:54:41.050
DAVID AUERBACH: Oh, boy.

00:54:41.050 --> 00:54:43.110
Knowing life-- I mean, God.

00:54:43.110 --> 00:54:46.060
You know, life cycles of
books are much slower.

00:54:46.060 --> 00:54:48.460
So it depends if--

00:54:48.460 --> 00:54:50.520
how-- next few years I hope.

00:54:50.520 --> 00:54:55.230
I hope sooner if the
publishing industry

00:54:55.230 --> 00:54:57.990
decides to speed up its cycles.

00:54:57.990 --> 00:55:00.750
But I mean there was
like a year turnaround

00:55:00.750 --> 00:55:03.540
after finishing this before
it actually came out.

00:55:03.540 --> 00:55:09.364
So it's-- I do miss the
rapid release cycles of, hey,

00:55:09.364 --> 00:55:10.530
I just [INAUDIBLE] this fix.

00:55:10.530 --> 00:55:11.370
Let's push it out.

00:55:11.370 --> 00:55:11.960
All right.

00:55:11.960 --> 00:55:13.091
Good night.

00:55:13.091 --> 00:55:15.090
If I could do that with
a book, that'd be great.

00:55:15.090 --> 00:55:17.119
That's why I still
blog sometimes

00:55:17.119 --> 00:55:19.410
just because being able to
write something and actually

00:55:19.410 --> 00:55:25.140
put it out there for consumption
the same day is amazing.

00:55:25.140 --> 00:55:27.376
And one of my most popular
pieces in the last year I

00:55:27.376 --> 00:55:28.500
actually went through that.

00:55:28.500 --> 00:55:31.230
And I had-- which was my
explanation of the finale

00:55:31.230 --> 00:55:31.980
of "Twin Peaks--

00:55:31.980 --> 00:55:34.890
The Return," which I wrote in
a couple of days, posted it.

00:55:34.890 --> 00:55:37.080
And apparently a lot
of people really wanted

00:55:37.080 --> 00:55:40.740
answers, because overnight
I get like literally

00:55:40.740 --> 00:55:43.440
like 10,000 times more
traffic than my little blog

00:55:43.440 --> 00:55:45.000
has ever seen before.

00:55:45.000 --> 00:55:45.824
[LAUGHTER]

00:55:45.824 --> 00:55:46.648
AUDIENCE: I agree.

00:55:46.648 --> 00:55:48.420
I watched like five episodes.

00:55:48.420 --> 00:55:50.770
And then I felt like it
doesn't make any sense.

00:55:50.770 --> 00:55:52.520
Like, there's like
horrible things.

00:55:52.520 --> 00:55:53.270
I didn't continue.

00:55:53.270 --> 00:55:54.500
But then I was curious.

00:55:54.500 --> 00:55:57.002
DAVID AUERBACH: I mean, what
I always told people-- look,

00:55:57.002 --> 00:55:59.460
if you're not enjoying it moment
to moment, don't watch it.

00:55:59.460 --> 00:56:01.470
You won't-- it's not worth it.

00:56:01.470 --> 00:56:04.220
But at the end of it, I
did want to know more.

00:56:04.220 --> 00:56:08.610
So anyway, thank you
very much, everybody.

00:56:08.610 --> 00:56:09.407
It's been great.

00:56:09.407 --> 00:56:09.990
It's been fun.

00:56:09.990 --> 00:56:13.340
[APPLAUSE]

